  "prompt": "What are the symptoms of eczema?",
  "response": "Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, can present various symptoms that may vary in severity and duration. Common symptoms include:\n\n1. **Dry, sensitive skin**: Skin may feel rough or tight and can be prone to irritation.\n2. **Red, inflamed patches**: Inflammation can cause redness and swelling in affected areas.\n3. **Itching**: This is often one of the most bothersome symptoms, which can lead to scratching and further irritation.\n4. **Rash**: Rashes can appear on various parts of the body, often on the face, neck, inside of elbows, behind knees, and on the hands and feet.\n5. **Thickened, leathery skin**: Chronic scratching can lead to lichenification, where the skin becomes thick and leathery.\n6. **Scaly or flaky skin**: Areas of affected skin may become scaly, flaking off as they dry out.\n7. **Bumps**: Small, raised, fluid-filled bumps may develop, which can ooze and crust over if scratched.\n8. **Discoloration**: The skin may become darker or lighter in affected areas.\n\nSymptoms can vary widely from person to person and may be triggered or worsened by allergens, irritants, stress, changes in temperature, and humidity levels. If you suspect you have eczema or are experiencing symptoms, it's advisable to consult a healthcare provider for a proper diagnosis and management plan.",
